value.0: Terriers are frequently bred in port cities all over Ruathym, and are highly valued as natural vermin catchers.  With very little training, they will intrepidly squeeze into small openings after rodents and other undesirable pests and kill them, helping to prevent the spread of disease.

Mouche is a lithe hound native to the region, whose breed is typically used for herding all sorts of livestock and even small children.  They are very loyal and gentle, making them good nanny dogs, but not frequently used for hunting game.

Bosk is war hound through and through, especially in Ruathym. Hundreds of pounds of compact muscle, stout form, strong jaws and endurance that is unbeatable make him live for the pounding of battle.                                                                                                                                                                                                     Bosk has mostly been retired from the ranks of war hound, however, after losing one of his eyes and sustaining a particularly gruesome gut wound.  He remains at the fortress, and has been relegated into a breeding program, which suits him just fine.

Above all else the Jarl's word is law. If he so deems anything to be a crime it is, regardless if it is on the following list or not. The Jarl's authority and his appointed subjects are not to be defied. They act in His name at all times and as such reserve the same right to enforce the laws in the best way to ensure the safety of the Jarl's lands and people. The following is a guideline for your actions while on his land but not a comprehensive list.

- The fortress is his home and Caraigh and Wiltun are his lands. Bring disrespect at your own peril.
- You are bound to obey the orders of the guards and the Jarl's appointed subjects when on both Wiltun and Caraigh lands. All orders not complied with shall meet swift and fitting punishment.
- Disrespecting the nobility of the Jarl's land will not be tolerated.
- Harassing the locals will not be tolerated.
- Any suspicious behavior will not be tolerated. This includes shadowdancing or attempting to hide from authority figures.
- In order to enter the settlements, you must remove anything that obscures your face and head so that the guards may plainly see who you are. It may be replaced after entering.
- While in the settlements weapons are to be put away including magical staves. The exception to this is any nonmagical walking sticks for the sake of the infirm.
- All spells are to be removed from your person before you enter the settlements and casting spells in the settlements is forbidden.
- Pets larger than an ordinary wolf are not allowed within the settlements without a special permit.
The Jarl's Word - Obey or be punished

The corpses of a few Luskan seafarers hang here, presumably pirates.  Raiding is frequent and common in the region, and the corpses than hang here are reasonably fresh.  The cold conflict between Ruathym and Luskan seems to catch friction every so often in Wiltun waters...

"Never was there a lily more elegant and soft. Commissioned by her father, Lord Arsant Wiltun V, 1383."

A young woman in the peak of her proposed fertility, made immortal in a beautiful marble slab.  Her elegance depicted in the statue seems to come from a dreamy distance the artist has captured in her eyes, which are cast upward and elsewhere. Whoever the artist was, it's clear they knew her very well.
Statue of the Fair Lady Oilanna

Dogma of Valkur: There is nothing more invigorating than challenging the elements. The feel of wind and spray on one's face and the deck pitching beneath one's feet is the greatest feeling in the world. If humankind is to expand its reach, daring men and women must defy the odds and dare the impossible. The thrill of exploration is sweeter than wine or rum. There is always risk, but without risk life is empty. Life is to be lived and damn the consequences. One's loyalties are first to one's mates, then to one's ship, and then to Valkur, who protects all sailors. Rely not on Valkur's hand to always extract you from difficulties, for such is coddling and leads to a lack of challenge and the room to grow. Rather, Valkur helps those actively solving their own problems by helping their plans work.

Dogma of Selune: Let all on whom Selune's light falls be welcome if they desire. As the silver moon waxes and wanes, so too does life. Trust in Selune's radiance, and know that all love alive under her light shall know her blessing. Turn to the moon, and she will be your true guide. Promote acceptance and tolerance. See all other beings as equals. Aid fellow Selunites as if they were your dearest friends.

Dogma of Tymora: One should be bold, for to be bold is to live. A brave heart and a willingness to take risks beat out a carefully wrought plan nine times out of ten. Place yourself in the hands of fate and trust to your own luck. Bear and conduct yourselves as your own masters, showing your good or bad fortune as confidence in the Lady. Chase your own unique goals, and the Lady aids the chase. Without direction or goals, you soon know the embrace of Beshaba, for those on no set course are at the mercy of misfortune, which has no mercy at all.
